{
  "texts": [
    "Now let's consider an initially less controversial notion: learning.",
    "Learning is a term widely used to describe the training of artificial systems, especially Deep Learning (DL) systems (e.g., LLMs).",
    "This notion, however, becomes problematic because it may lead people to attribute other directly related features (e.g., experience, competence, flexibility, and even wisdom) to AI, features that are currently hardly applicable to AI systems.",
    "Even if there is a basic analogy between what happens in the human brain 3 We do not engage here with an important and ultimately complementary issue that we will be addressing in a different paper: the role of conceptual engineering as a response to the conceptual disruption caused by emerging technologies (see, for example, [37,59]).",
    "The responsible conceptualization that we propose might be seen as a component of conceptual engineering understood as conceptual adaptation (or even amelioration)."
  ]
}